					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">Not really. Every even harmonic is 0, correctly, but every second odd harmonic is going to be negative; a square wave would have all positive harmonics. (It would sound the same, but the shape is different, not square.)<br /><div class="attachtitle">Attachment:</div><div class="attachcontent">
			<span class="gensmall"><b>File comment:</b> What it looks like if you invert every second harmonic.</span><br />
		
			<a href="./download/file.php?id=5274&amp;sid=4a5d29e2780379a69b5b5cc4aee955ec&amp;mode=view"><img src="./download/file.php?id=5274&amp;t=1&amp;sid=4a5d29e2780379a69b5b5cc4aee955ec" alt="unsquare.png" /></a><br />
			<span class="gensmall">unsquare.png [ 12.66 KiB | Viewed 390 times ]</span>
		

		<br />
	</div><br /><a href="https://codepen.io/anon/pen/ONpJQN" class="postlink">JavaScript demonstration</a><br /><br />I'm not quite sure why this interesting, though?<br /><br /><em>sin(x * π/2) = 0, 1, 0, -1, 0, 1, 0, -1...</em> (for <em>x</em> in natural numbers)<br /><br />So really we're just looking at <em>1/x</em>, but omitting every second one, and inverting every fourth one.<br /><br /><em>1/x</em> is the magnitude of harmonics in a saw wave.<br /><br /><em>1/x</em> is the magnitude of odd harmonics in a square wave, 0 for even harmonics.<br /><br /><em>1/x<sup>2</sup></em> is the magnitude of odd harmonics in a triangle wave if you invert every second one, 0 for even harmonics.<br /><br />You can find others via calculus and the <a href="http://mathworld.wolfram.com/FourierSeries.html" class="postlink">Fourier Series</a>, or just looking them up I suppose.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

