				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">Well, I fail to see how it's <em>not</em> interesting. If you see something like this as a mathematician, you should investigate if there's something to it. As it turns out, the sinc function <em>is</em> somewhat related to the square wave harmonic coefficients. This is beautifully demonstrated in the video below using a 100 year old mechanical computer, Albert Michelson's Harmonic Analyzer. <br /><br />Synthesis: <!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8KmVDxkia_w">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8KmVDxkia_w</a><!-- m --><br /><br />Analysis: <!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6dW6VYXp9HM">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6dW6VYXp9HM</a><!-- m --><br /><br />The machine is using rocker arms to set coefficients for cosine harmonics and plot a waveform from it's harmonics. But it can also do analysis, where you input an arbitrary waveform, and the plotted graph gives you back cosine coefficients for said waveform, at discrete intervals in the output. In fact, the second video linked above demonstrates almost exactly what psycopathicteen noted in the original post. The machine has 20 rocker arms for setting coefficients. The presenter is entering a square wave by setting the first 10 arms to full magnitude and the last 10 arms to zero magnitude. But this also corresponds to the synthesis of cos(x)+cos(2x)+cos(3x)+...+cos(10x). This function, as it happens, makes a rather good local approximation of the sinc function.<br /><br />You can compare the two by entering the following into Wolfram Alpha. I've offset the sine series and tweaked the coefficients of the sinc to make them fit. <br /><a href="http://www.wolframalpha.com/input/?i=cos(x)%2Bcos(2x)%2Bcos(3x)%2Bcos(4x)%2Bcos(5x)%2Bcos(6x)%2Bcos(7x)%2Bcos(8x)%2Bcos(9x)%2Bcos(10x)%2B.5,sinc(10.5x)*11.5" class="postlink">cos(x)+cos(2x)+cos(3x)+cos(4x)+cos(5x)+cos(6x)+cos(7x)+cos(8x)+cos(9x)+cos(10x)+.5,sinc(10.5x)*11.5</a></div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

