					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">Maybe this will be more interesting.<br /><br />If you sample an NTSC video signal at 12Mhz, and want to filter out the 3.58Mhz color carrier signal, an easy way of creating a filter is to think about the frequency plot as a square wave from 1 to 0, that goes through .5 at exactly 3Mhz, but crosses 0 at 3.58Mhz.  The middle filter coefficient would be .5, and each odd coefficient could be thought of as adding harmonics to the square wave until it's square enough, and/or adjust it so it crosses the bottom at 3.58Mhz.<br /><br />For example, if you have an image that is 320 NTSC square pixels, you can double it to 640, and filter out the chroma signal with this filter, {-49, 0, 113, 128, 113, 0, -49} and then dividing it by 256.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

