					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">Sik wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I was taught that a square wave contains every harmonic in it.</div><br />No, it contains only every second harmonic. The saw wave contains every harmonic.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">Sik wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">This is one of the reasons why oscilloscopes include a square wave generator: if you feed it back to the oscillator, and notice some distortion in the corners (i.e. they aren't as sharp as they should be) it means some frequency range is getting filtered out, which means there's a problem you should fix to avoid getting invalid results when doing actual work.</div><br />A square wave is easy to generate, and a good diagnostic, yes. Despite not having as many harmonics as the saw wave, it's probably easier to read a malformed square wave than it is a saw wave.</div>

